dialogs.original: Masters, play here, I will content your pains.Something thats brief, and bid Good morrow, general.
dialogs.translated: Gentlemen, play some music here. I'll pay you for your trouble. Play a short song, and then say, "Good morning, general."

dialogs.original: Why masters, have your instruments been in Naples, thatthey speak i' th' nose thus?
dialogs.translated: Gentlemen, have your instruments been in Naples? Is that why they have that strange nasal sound?

dialogs.original: How, sir? How?
dialogs.translated: What do you mean, sir?

dialogs.original: Are these, I pray you, wind instruments?
dialogs.translated: Tell me, are these wind instruments?

dialogs.original: Ay, marry, are they, sir.
dialogs.translated: Yes, indeed they are, sir.

dialogs.original: Oh, thereby hangs a tail.
dialogs.translated: Well, that's an problem.

dialogs.original: Whereby hangs a tale, sir?
dialogs.translated: What's the problem, sir?

dialogs.original: Marry sir, by many a wind instrument that I know. But,masters, heres money for you, and the general so likesyour music that he desires you, for loves sake, to make no more noise with it.
dialogs.translated: Indeed, sir, windbags!  They're the problem. But, gentlemen, here's some money for you. The general likes your music so much that he would like you to stop playing it, for God's sake.

dialogs.original: Well, sir, we will not.
dialogs.translated: Well then, sir, we will stop.

dialogs.original: If you have any music that may not be heard, to t again. But, as they say, to hear music the general does not greatly care.
dialogs.translated: If you have any songs that are silent, feel free to keep playing those. But, you know, the general doesn't care much for music.

dialogs.original: We have none such, sir.
dialogs.translated: We don't have any silent songs, sir.

dialogs.original: Then put up your pipes in your bag, for Ill away. Go, vanish into air, away!
dialogs.translated: Then pack up your instruments and go. Vanish into the air. Go!

dialogs.original: Dost thou hear, my honest friend?
dialogs.translated: Do you hear, my honest friend?

dialogs.original: No, I hear not your honest friend, I hear you.
dialogs.translated: No, I don't hear your honest friend. I hear you.

dialogs.original: Prithee, keep up thy quillets. Theres a poor piece of gold for thee. If the gentlewoman that attends the generals wife be stirring,   tell her theres one Cassio entreats her a little favour of speech. Wilt thou do this?
dialogs.translated: Please, that's enough of your jokes. Here's a little gold for you.  If the woman who takes care of the general's wife is awake, tell her that a man named Cassio begs the she give him a chance to speak with her. Will you do this?

dialogs.original: She is stirring, sir. If she will stir hither, I shall seem to notify unto her.
dialogs.translated: She is awake, sir. If she happens to come this way, I'll tell her.

dialogs.original: In happy time, Iago.
dialogs.translated: Just in time, Iago.

dialogs.original: You have not been abed, then?
dialogs.translated: You haven't gone to bed, then?

dialogs.original: Why, no. The day had broke    Before we parted. I have made bold, Iago,    To send in to your wife.   My suit to her    Is that she will to virtuous Desdemona    Procure me some access.
dialogs.translated: No. It was already daytime when we left each other. Iago, I've been bold enough to ask to speak to your wife. I will ask her to allow me to see the virtuous Desdemona.

dialogs.original: Ill send her to you presently,    And Ill devise a mean to draw the Moor    Out of the way,   that your converse and business    May be more free.
dialogs.translated: I'll send her to you right away. And I'll figure out a way to take the Moor somewhere out of the way, so that you can talk to her in private.

dialogs.original: I humbly thank you fort.
dialogs.translated: I humbly thank you for this.

dialogs.original: I never knew a Florentine more kind and honest.
dialogs.translated: I've never known a kinder, more honest man from Florence.

dialogs.original: Good morrow, good Lieutenant. I am sorry    For your displeasure, but all will sure be well.    The general and his wife are talking of it,    And she speaks for you stoutly.   The Moor replies    That he you hurt is of great fame in Cyprus    And great affinity, and that in wholesome wisdom    He might not but refuse you.   But he protests he loves you    And needs no other suitor but his likings    To take the safest occasion by the front    To bring you in again.
dialogs.translated: Good morning, good Lieutenant. I am sorry for what has happened to you, but I'm sure everything will turn out okay. The general and his wife are talking about the situation, and Desdemona is speaking up for you. Othello says that the man you hurt is well-known and well-liked in Cyprus, and that he has no choice but to refuse your appeal. But Othello insists that he still loves you, and doesn't need any persuading to put you back in your position when he gets the opportunity.

dialogs.original: Yet I beseech you,    If you think fit, or that it may be done,    Give me advantage of some brief discourse    With Desdemona alone.
dialogs.translated: Nonetheless, I beg youif you think it's possible and a good ideato let me talk with Desdemona alone for a little bit.

dialogs.original: Pray you come in.I will bestow you where you shall have timeTo speak your bosom freely.
dialogs.translated: Please, come inside. I will give you a chance to talk to her freely.

dialogs.original: I am much bound to you.
dialogs.translated: I owe you for this.
